dfischer.utils

Class PerformanceDataRecord

  • java.lang.Object
    • dfischer.utils.PerformanceDataRecord

  • public class PerformanceDataRecord
extends java.lang.Object
    Contains the measured performance data of an execution step (thread step). Collects all data of one specific execution step over all concurrent users and loops.

    The most methods return only for a measured URL a meaningful result. For a page break the following subset of methods is valid:

    • getAveragePageBreakDelay()
    • getDataType()¹
    • getInfoText()¹
    • getPerformanceDataObject()¹
    • isValidPageBreak()
    • getPercentile()¹
    • getPerformanceDataTicks()¹
    • setScreenshotImage()
    • hasScreenshotImage()
    • getScreenshotImage()
    • readObject()¹
    • toString()¹
    • writeObject()¹
    ¹ valid for page breaks and URLs

    The following methods are only valid for URLs:

    • getAverageNetworkEstablishTime()
    • getAverageRequestTransmitTime()
    • getAverageResponseContentReceiveTime()
    • getAverageResponseHeaderReceiveTime()
    • getAverageResponseHeaderWaitTime()
    • getAverageSize()
    • getAverageTime()²
    • getBasicFailureMap()
    • getFailedCount()
    • getFailedUrl()
    • getFailureInfo()
    • getFailureActionType()
    • getMaxTime()²
    • getMinTime()²
    • getPassedCount()²
    • getTotalSize()
    • isValidPerformanceData()
    ² valid also for page breaks for results measured by version 5.0-A or later

    Hint: check first the kind of data by using the method getDataType().

    Measured times of URLs:

     <-dns resolve time-><- socket connect time-><-ssl handshake time-><-request transmit time-><-response header wait time-><-response header receive time-><-response content receive time->
 <------------------------------------------------------average (=total) time------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------>
    See Also:
    getDataType(), PerformanceData.getPerformanceDataRecord(int), PerformanceData.getPerformanceDataRecord(), PerformanceData.isValidPerformanceData(int), PerformanceData.getPageOfUrl(int)

      • getPassedPerformanceDataTicks

        public PerformanceDataTick[] getPassedPerformanceDataTicks()
        Returns the date and time and the response time of all single measured values of the (same) URL call or web page. The number of measured data ticks dependes on the value of the percentile sampling rate, which is set in the constructor of the PerformanceData object.
        Note 1: the result is not sorted by time.
        Note 2: the result returns only data ticks of successful passed calls of web pages or URLs.
        Returns:
        The measured data ticks for this URL call or web page.
        See Also:
        PerformanceDataTick.sortByDateAndTime(dfischer.utils.PerformanceDataTick[]), getPercentile()

        Note 2: the result returns only data ticks of successful passed calls of web pages or URLs.
        Parameters:
        startPointInTime - point in time (since January 1, 1970) from which the measured data ticks will be flow into the result, -1 = no start point in time (collect from the beginning of the load test)
        endPointInTime - point in time (since January 1, 1970) after which the measured data ticks will not flow into the result, -1 = no end point in time (collect up to the latest time)
        Returns:
        an object which contains the measured data ticks for this URL call or web page

      • getBasicFailureMap

        public PerformanceDataRecordBasicFailureMap getBasicFailureMap()
        Return basic information about all failed URL calls.
        The basic information contains only the following data for each failed URL call:
        1. The status type of the failed URL call
        2. The HTTP status code of the failed URL call
        3. The time in milliseconds when the error has occurred (since January 1, 1970)
        Note: more detailed data about failed URL calls (error snapshots) are available by calling getFailureInfo() and getFailedUrl(). However, the total number of error snapshots is limited which means that getFailureInfo() and getFailedUrl() may not return all errors - in contrast to this method which return data for all failed URL calls.
        See Also:
        getFailureInfo(), getFailedUrl(PerformanceDataRecordFailureInfo failureInfo)
